[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at this real estate agent. &gt;&gt; Seriously, stop scrolling. You are not ready for what\'s inside this house. &gt;&gt; He\'s walking, talking, and interacting with the furniture. But here\'s the truth. He doesn\'t exist. [music] Neither does the house. This was fully'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated with Cling AI [music] 3.0. Today, I\'m going to show you the exact workflows [music] for every single shot. when to use just a start frame, when you'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absolutely need an end [music] frame, and when to use multi-shot. We will test everything from camera drones to changing seasons, product reveals, [music] and human avatars.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s see if Cling is finally production ready. We start with exteriors. I generated these base images with Nano Banana Pro. For this first batch, my workflow is simple. I upload only a'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start frame. [music] I want to control the camera purely with prompts. First test, an FPV [music] drone shot. The movement is smooth, but for some reason, Cling switched to a'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fisheye lens halfway through. [music] It\'s not bad for a first try, but a bit weird. Next, a focus pull. This worked surprisingly well. [music] The depth of field shift is super clean.'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then I tried a low angle [music] shot. It understood the task and the animation looks pretty well. But the winner here is the crane [music] shot. Just by prompting craneshot moving'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up, we [music] got this. The geometry stays stable and the parallax is perfect. By the way, I [music] have posted every single prompt used in this'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video directly in our community Discord. It\'s a great place to share your own results and learn from others. The link is right down in the video description. Make sure to [music] join us there. Now,'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s try changing seasons. I generated four different seasonal [music] views in Nano Banana Pro. First, I tried describing the change in the prompt [music] and using only two views as'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'input. The result is all right. Nothing special to be honest. [music] Then I tried Cling Omni 3.0 with multi-shot and all four reference images. This gave me pure slop. The'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transitions are so bad and random. I don\'t like it. I decided to [music] use a start and end frame and do each transition in one animation.'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This way I got way more control and just typing [music] timelapse as prompt was enough to deliver four working transitions. For mood changes like day to night,'

[02:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] I changed the workflow. I used a start frame and an end frame. The geometry in both frames must be identical. If you stick to this, you get perfect B-roll'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] material. For this pool shot, I went back to start frame only and just prompted for weather physics. Subtle rain, wind, [music] fog. Cling\'s'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'physics engine handles water ripples and atmosphere really well. Now moving inside, furnishing an empty apartment. Start [music] frame is the'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'empty shell. End frame is fully furnished. I ran three specific tests to see how Cling handles [music] the transition. Test one, stop motion. I prompted for a'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'choppy frame by frame appearance. It gives a really technical architectural vibe. The grow up effect. The furniture scales up from the floor. It\'s a bit smoother'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'though. You can see some artifacts where the rug generates. Falling down, furniture [music] dropping from the ceiling. This one felt the most dynamic, even if the physics aren\'t 100%'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] perfect yet. Now, let\'s switch interior styles. Start frame [music] equals style A, end frame equals style B. Crucial rule. The geometry of the room,'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'walls, windows must be identical. First, a standard eye level view. The morph is solid. No major glitches. I tried to use a different view then and'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'switched to a top-down image [music] of the room. This one is flawless. The AI has zero trouble. Then I pushed [music] it with a low angle view. Usually AI'

[04:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'struggles with floor planes here, but Cling kept all the furniture consistent during the swap. And finally, [music] a macro shot of the couch fabric.'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is more of a B-roll animation. But mixing [music] these detail shots in with the wide angles prevents your presentation from looking boring and repetitive. Now, let\'s look at product.'

[05:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] Imagine we need a commercial for this lamp. I uploaded different angles from Nano Banana Pro and set a start and end frame. I used multi-shot and explained'

[05:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompts for each segment to define the boundaries because I told the AI exactly where to start and end. The animation and the cuts are nearly perfect.'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It doesn\'t always work though. This cupboard was a fail. The frames weren\'t 100% identical or maybe my prompt had errors. Cling does not forgive mistakes'

[05:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. For an armchair animation, I tried using start and end frame. Again, this [music] worked great. Simple and effective animation to present furniture, but manufacturers need to'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show functionality. They need humans to sell the lifestyle. I generated different views in Nano Banana Pro. some already including the models. For animation, I use start'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frames only and describe the specific action for each scene with a prompt. Shot one, the wide [music] shot. Just the armchair in the room to establish'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'context. The lighting is consistent. The shadows [music] are correct. Solid start. Shot two. An over- the-sh shoulder view. [music] I prompted for a person sitting in the chair reading a'

[06:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'book. Watch closely the slight head movement, [music] the hand holding the book. It feels surprisingly organic and not stiff like older AI models. Shot three, a detailed shot of the chair'

[06:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'itself. Cling kept the texture sharp without hallucinating weird patterns. And finally, shot four. the model from a distance [music]'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just moving naturally around the space. This adds that dynamic lifestyle vibe that every client asks for. All of these work straight out of the box with simple prompting. A massive timesaver. [music]'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Speaking of humans, what about general crowds? For exteriors, I just took a building photo and prompted people moving naturally. Solid result usable'

[07:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for background life. For interiors, I had Nano Banana Pro insert the person into the start frame first. Then I prompted the action. It looks a tiny bit'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sloppy compared to the furniture, [music] but it absolutely serves the purpose for storytelling. Finally, the most exciting part. We are building [music] Tim, our AI real estate'

[07:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agent. Usually AI characters look different in every single shot. To fix this, I used Cling\'s character consistency tab. I uploaded a few reference images of Tim'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and gave him a name. Now, whenever I use the name Tim in a prompt, Cling knows exactly what he looks like. Let\'s start the tour.'

[08:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I wanted a smooth camera move starting wide showing [music] the agent and the house and then pushing in to a closeup of his face. I generated the voice over text directly inside Clling.'

[08:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Seriously, stop scrolling. You are not ready for what\'s inside this house. &gt;&gt; The camera move is cinematic and the lip syncing is spoton. He feels present. Shot two, the kitchen. This was the'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hardest physics test. I wanted Tim to walk to [music] the table and sit down. Attempt one. &gt;&gt; You think the design is crazy? Wait until you see the living room. It looked'

[09:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sloppy. The AI struggled with the physics of the body meeting the chair. It looked like he melted into it. But watch attempt two. This is fascinating.'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; You think the design is crazy? Wait until you see the living room. Clling realized the transition was too difficult, so it automatically inserted a camera cut right as he sits down. It'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'essentially [music] edited the video for me to hide the glitch. Shot three, the living room. Here, I just wanted him to sit comfortably on the couch and continue'

[09:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the story. The focus here was on posture. &gt;&gt; But honestly, the kitchen is for show. This is where you actually live. Friday movie nights, unbeatable. He doesn\'t look stiff. He looks relaxed. The consistency holds up perfectly. It\'s'

[09:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clearly the same guy from the kitchen. Shot four, the home office. I challenged the model with object interaction. The prompt was, "Show the room." Then Tim'

[10:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'slightly touches the office [music] chair. &gt;&gt; And here, no zoom background needed, just pure focus. &gt;&gt; Hands are usually a nightmare for AI. But look at the contact point. He'

[10:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brushes the chair naturally. It anchors him in the reality of the [music] scene. Final shot, the outro. I wanted a complex blocking. Tim walks into the frame from behind the camera. [music]'

[10:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Stops to deliver his final line and then walks out of the frame towards the house. &gt;&gt; So, are you moving in or am I? DM me home now. Peace. &gt;&gt; The [music] tracking is amazing.'

[10:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'He enters, hits his mark, lips move perfectly, and he exits. No sliding feet, no morphing. So, verdict on cling 3.0. [music]'

[10:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The physics are a massive upgrade from 2.6, and the multishot feature is a lifesaver for avoiding glitches in long sequences or transitions. I really wanted to'

[11:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] go even deeper into the details today. But we are just running out of time. There is so much potential in Cling 3.0 that I feel like we only scratched the'

[11:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'surface. I\'ve dropped the specific prompts I used for all the shots in our community. Discord link is in the description. If this breakdown helped you, hit that like'

[11:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'button [music] to help the channel grow and I\'ll see you in the next one.'
